, sex worker activists in Brazil, rural feminists in Nicaragua, to domestic violence organizations for Latina immigrants in Texas. Each essay addresses two themes: telling stories and taking risks. The authors understand women activists across the Americas as storytellers who, along with the authors themselves, work to fill the Latin American and Caribbean studies archives with histories of resistance. In addition to sharing the activists' stories, the contributors weave in discussions of scholarly risk taking to speak to the challenges and importance of elevating the storytellers and their histories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFeminism -- History -- North America. 0aFeminism -- History -- South America. 0aFeminismzNorth AmericaxHistory. 0aFeminismzSouth AmericaxHistory. 0aSocial justice -- History -- North America. 0aSocial justice -- History -- South America. 0aSocial justicezNorth AmericaxHistory. 0aSocial justicezSouth AmericaxHistory. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 a Fleites-Lear, Marisela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a MarÍn, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcia, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrabe, Shelly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeissle, Kristy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLettvin, Mahala, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManfredi, Jessica Monteiro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarko, Tamera, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab